# Shocking concurrent edits: stop protocol

When working in a multi-agent workspace, treat surprising file changes as a safety event.

## Trigger

- A file changes unexpectedly while you are editing it.
- You detect broad or surprising diffs that do not match your recent commands.
- Another agent appears to have touched the same file or tightly coupled config during your task window.

## Required actions

- Stop writing immediately in the affected file(s).
- Re-read the latest file state and compare against your intended change before any further edit.
- Ask the user how to proceed if ownership is unclear or behavior could be clobbered.
- Resume only after the user confirms direction or file ownership boundaries are re-established.

## Tie-breaker

If this rule conflicts with speed or automation goals, prefer this rule. Preventing clobber/regression in shared workspaces takes priority.
